{
  "answer": "**Bṛhaspati Smṛti** and **Kātyāyana Smṛti** describe judicial ordeals, referred to as *divya pramāṇa* or \"divine proof\" (*divya pramāṇa*), which encompasses various tests like the balance ordeal, *dharma* ordeal, poison, water, fire, and others, used in legal disputes when human proofs (witnesses, documents, possession) are inconclusive.[^1][^2][^3][^4]\n\nNo other works in the corpus cover this topic in a legal/judicial context; isolated mentions of \"ordeal\" elsewhere (e.g., in poetry or metaphorically) do not refer to judicial procedures.\n\n[^1]: Bṛhaspati Smṛti, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-510297).\n[^2]: Bṛhaspati Smṛti, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-500986).\n[^3]: Kātyāyana Smṛti, Chapter 24, [paragraph](/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/24/translation/#p-d37d5d).\n[^4]: Kātyāyana Smṛti, Chapter 24, [paragraph](/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/24/translation/#p-b4ce2a).",
